        },
        "body": "This C++ program implements a Breadth-First Search (BFS) traversal starting from node 0 in a directed graph. The graph is represented using an adjacency list. The main function demonstrates the BFS traversal on two example graphs and also includes a simple error check for invalid input.\r\n\r\nKey Components:\r\n\r\nbfs_from_zero Function:\r\n\r\nTakes the number of vertices ([V](vscode-file://vscode-app/Applications/Visual%20Studio%20Code.app/Contents/Resources/app/out/vs/code/electron-browser/workbench/workbench.html)) and an adjacency list ([adj](vscode-file://vscode-app/Applications/Visual%20Studio%20Code.app/Contents/Resources/app/out/vs/code/electron-browser/workbench/workbench.html)) as input.\r\nPerforms BFS starting from node 0.\r\nReturns the order in which nodes are visited.\r\nMain Function:\r\n\r\nDefines two example graphs and prints the BFS traversal order for each.\r\nDemonstrates error handling for invalid vertex count.\r\nUsage:\r\nThis code is useful for understanding how BFS works on graphs and how to implement it efficiently using standard C++ libraries.",
